---
import CaseStudyLayout from "../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro";
import ArchitectureDiagram from "../../components/ArchitectureDiagram.astro";
import PrismCode from "../../components/PrismCode.astro";

const title = "Job Application Automation — Case Study · Tyler Dobson";
const description =
  "A multi-agent AI workflow with eight integrated tools, running on Zapier, GPT-4o, Claude, and GitHub. Built by Tyler Dobson.";

const toolTable = [
  ["Google Forms", "Manual job application entry"],
  ["Google Sheets", "Master tracker database (23 fields, AI-enriched rows)"],
  ["Zapier", "No-code automation engine, 5 active Zaps"],
  ["Gmail", "Detects confirmations, recruiter replies, interview requests"],
  ["Google Calendar", "Follow-up reminders and interview prep blocks"],
  ["GPT-4o", "Structured extraction: skills, companies, roles, JSON normalization"],
  [
    "Anthropic Claude",
    "Reasoning: fit scoring, summaries, follow-up drafting, recommendations",
  ],
  ["GitHub", "Version control for prompts, scripts, docs, automation specs"],
];

const masterFields = [
  "Application ID",
  "Date Applied",
  "Company",
  "Job Title",
  "Job Link",
  "Platform",
  "Location",
  "Work Format",
  "Internship Type",
  "Status",
  "Priority",
  "Resume Version",
  "Cover Letter Used",
  "Recruiter Name",
  "Recruiter Email",
  "Skills Mentioned",
  "AI Fit Score",
  "AI Summary",
  "Next Action",
  "Follow-Up Date",
  "Interview Date",
  "Notes",
  "Last Updated",
];

const zap1 = `Trigger:  New Google Form response
Steps:
  1. Format the form response
  2. Send job title + company + notes + link to GPT-4o → extract skills, summary
  3. Send extracted context to Claude → fit score, next action
  4. Append enriched row to Google Sheets Master Tracker
  5. Create Google Calendar follow-up event 7 days out`;

const zap2 = `Trigger:  New Gmail email matching application-confirmation patterns
Steps:
  1. GPT extracts company and role from the email body
  2. Check Master Tracker for a matching row
  3. If match: update status → "Application Confirmed"
  4. If no match: insert new row, source tag "Gmail Auto-Detected"`;

const zap3 = `Trigger:  Daily at 8:00 AM
Steps:
  1. Query Master Tracker for rows where Follow-Up Date = today and Status ≠ closed
  2. For each row, generate a follow-up email with Claude (drafts only, never auto-send)
  3. Save draft to Gmail
  4. Create a Calendar reminder`;

const zap4 = `Trigger:  New Gmail email classified as interview request
Steps:
  1. Claude classifies email type and extracts interview metadata
  2. Update Master Tracker status → "Interview Scheduled"
  3. Create Calendar event with interview details
  4. Generate prep checklist into the Master Tracker notes column`;

const zap5 = `Trigger:  New Gmail email matching rejection patterns
Steps:
  1. GPT extracts company and role
  2. Update Master Tracker status → "Closed - Rejected"
  3. Log to weekly summary sheet for retrospective analysis`;

const repoStructure = `job-application-automation/
├── README.md
├── workflow-spec.md
├── prompts/
│   ├── extract_job_info.md
│   ├── score_job_fit.md
│   ├── draft_follow_up.md
│   └── classify_gmail.md
├── google-apps-script/
│   ├── dedupe_rows.gs
│   ├── update_status.gs
│   └── calendar_followups.gs
├── zapier/
│   ├── zap_1_form_to_sheet.md
│   ├── zap_2_gmail_confirmation.md
│   ├── zap_3_followup_reminder.md
│   ├── zap_4_interview_detection.md
│   └── zap_5_rejection_tracking.md
└── docs/
    ├── sheet_schema.md
    ├── status_options.md
    └── setup_checklist.md`;
---

<CaseStudyLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <p
    class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-accent"
    style="font-family: var(--font-mono);"
  >
    Flagship case study
  </p>

  <h1
    class="mt-3 font-light leading-[1.1] tracking-tight text-text"
    style="font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3.25rem);"
  >
    Job Application Automation System
  </h1>

  <p class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    A multi-agent AI workflow with eight integrated tools, running on Zapier, GPT-4o, Claude,
    and GitHub.
  </p>

  <p
    class="mt-5 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-text-muted"
    style="font-family: var(--font-mono);"
  >
    2026 · Personal Project · Active System
  </p>

  <p class="mt-6">
    <a href="/" class="text-sm text-text-dim hover:text-accent transition-colors">
      ← Back to portfolio
    </a>
  </p>

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">The problem</h2>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    I was applying to internships at a rate I couldn't manually track. Rows in a spreadsheet,
    half-remembered follow-ups, recruiter emails buried in Gmail, no signal on which roles were
    worth my time and which were dead ends. The applications themselves weren't the bottleneck —
    the operational overhead of running a serious job search was.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    So I built the system I would have wanted from day one.
  </p>

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">System architecture</h2>
  <div class="-mx-2 my-8 sm:-mx-6">
    <ArchitectureDiagram variant="large" />
  </div>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    The system has eight integrated tools and a clean separation of concerns. Google Forms is
    the manual entry point. Zapier is the automation engine — every event flows through a Zap.
    Google Sheets is the source of truth: every application, every status update, every
    AI-generated field lives in one master tracker. GPT-4o handles structured extraction —
    turning messy job descriptions and recruiter emails into clean JSON. Claude handles
    reasoning — scoring fit, summarizing roles, drafting follow-up emails, recommending next
    actions. Gmail is both an input (detecting confirmations, recruiter replies, interview
    requests) and an output (drafting follow-ups). Google Calendar handles the timing layer.
    GitHub is the control center, version-controlling the prompts, scripts, and workflow
    documentation.
  </p>

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">Tool responsibilities</h2>
  <div class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-border">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-elev">
          <th
            class="border-b border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.12em] text-text-muted"
            style="font-family: var(--font-mono);"
          >
            Tool
          </th>
          <th
            class="border-b border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.12em] text-text-muted"
            style="font-family: var(--font-mono);"
          >
            Role
          </th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          toolTable.map(([tool, role]) => (
            <tr class="border-t border-border first:border-t-0">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top font-medium text-text">{tool}</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top text-text-dim">{role}</td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">Why two LLMs?</h2>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    GPT and Claude have different strengths, and assigning them by capability instead of using
    one for everything is what makes the system reliable.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    GPT-4o gets structured extraction. It's fast, cheap, and unusually good at producing valid
    JSON on the first try. Every Zap that needs a clean field — extract the company from this
    email, normalize this skill list, classify whether this message is an interview request —
    goes through GPT.
  </p>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    Claude gets reasoning and writing. Fit scores on a 1-10 scale with justification.
    Two-sentence summaries that emphasize what actually matters. Follow-up emails written in my
    voice. Recommendations for next actions based on application context. This is where output
    quality matters more than speed or cost.
  </p>

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">The five Zaps</h2>

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">Zap 1 — Form to Master Tracker</h3>
  <PrismCode code={zap1} />

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">Zap 2 — Gmail confirmation detection</h3>
  <PrismCode code={zap2} />

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">Zap 3 — Daily follow-up scheduler</h3>
  <PrismCode code={zap3} />

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">Zap 4 — Interview detection</h3>
  <PrismCode code={zap4} />

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">Zap 5 — Rejection / closure tracking</h3>
  <PrismCode code={zap5} />

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">The Master Tracker schema</h2>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    Twenty-three columns, every row enriched by the system as it moves through the pipeline.
  </p>
  <div class="mt-6 grid grid-cols-2 gap-x-6 gap-y-2 rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-elev p-6 font-mono text-sm text-text-dim" style="font-family: var(--font-mono);">
    {masterFields.map((field) => <span>{field}</span>)}
  </div>

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">Repository structure</h2>
  <PrismCode code={repoStructure} />

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-light text-text">What I learned</h2>
  <p class="mt-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    Three takeaways from running this system on my own job search for the past several weeks.
  </p>

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">
    1. Separate capabilities, don't multiplex one model.
  </h3>
  <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    Using GPT for extraction and Claude for reasoning produced consistently better output than
    either model trying to do both. The temptation to use a single model for everything is real,
    and it's a quality-killer.
  </p>

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">2. Drafts beat auto-send every time.</h3>
  <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    Early versions of the system tried to auto-send follow-up emails. The drafts were good —
    but not as good as me reading them, adjusting one or two phrases, and sending in 15
    seconds. The human-in-the-loop is the right tradeoff for outbound communication.
  </p>

  <h3 class="mt-8 text-lg font-medium text-text">3. The Sheet is the database. Treat it like one.</h3>
  <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-text-dim">
    Schema discipline matters. Status enums matter. Last-updated timestamps matter. The moment
    I treated Google Sheets like a real source of truth instead of a scratchpad, the rest of
    the system became reliable.
  </p>

  <hr class="my-12 border-border" />

  <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-bg-elev p-6 sm:p-8">
    <p class="text-base leading-relaxed text-text">
      Want to talk about the system, or you're hiring for AI / Data Engineering roles? Email me:
      <a
        href="mailto:tydobson41@gmail.com"
        class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover underline-offset-4 hover:underline"
      >
        tydobson41@gmail.com
      </a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</CaseStudyLayout>
